Pauses full inventory between filesystem operations. Does not apply to Add Shows.}\cell\row\pard \trowd\trql\trleft5\ltrrow\trkeep\trpaddft3\trpaddt0\trpaddfl3\trpaddl0\trpaddfb3\trpaddb0\trpaddfr3\trpaddr0\clbrdrt\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clbrdrl\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clpadft3\clpadt108\clbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clbrdrr\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clpadfr3\clpadr108\cellx5183\clbrdrt\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clbrdrl\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clpadft3\clpadt108\clbrdrb\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clbrdrr\brdrs\brdrw10\brdrcf1\clpadfr3\clpadr108\cellx10362\pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\intbl\sl240\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa20{\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\langfe1033\loch
Resume}\cell\pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\intbl\sl240\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa20{\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\loch\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\langfe1033\loch
Resumes a paused full inventory. Repeated Resume clicks report only when a pause is active.}\cell\row\pard \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Performance modes}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Search-path worker count is capped by the number of search paths queued for that run. Postprocess setlist/bootlist export uses a separate bounded worker pool after scanning finishes.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
gentle: best when using external drives, spinning disks, or Windows desktops where responsiveness matters. Uses 1 worker by default.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
balanced: moderate parallelism. GUI and CLI default performance mode. Typically uses up to 2 workers by default.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
fast: higher normal throughput, usually up to the CPU count by default.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
extreme: speed-first for inventory traversal. Search-path worker dispatch has no performance-mode worker cap unless Max Workers is set to a positive value. Postprocess still uses a bounded thread pool and honors Max Workers when set. Extreme does not skip non-compliant tag checks.}
\par \pard\plain \s1\rtlch\af14\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb480\sa0\keepn\cf17\f8\fs32\b\dbch\af10{\loch
9. Compliant versus non-compliant mode}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80\loch

\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\qc\sb0\sa80{\loch
Figure 5. Compliant mode trusts strict folder patterns; non-compliant mode uses more flexible matching and fallback information.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Compliant mode}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80{\loch
Use Compliant mode when folders intentionally follow predictable naming. The main supported forms are String1 Date String2, String1 - String2, and String1 Date. For Date, TLO first looks for yyyy-mm-dd and then accepted year ranges before falling back to older date-recognition rules. In compliant mode, FLAC tags are not read or used.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
String1 Date String2: String1 is the artist text, Date is normalized, and String2 is kept as the trailing show text unless online lookup fills venue/location. When starting a compliant run, choose Master to check String1 against the artist database, or As-Is to use String1 directly with no lookup.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
String1 - String2: String2 is treated as an album/show tail. A parenthetical-only tail such as (Live) is preserved.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
String1 Date: fallback when no String2 exists; show name becomes Artist Date. It uses the same Master or As-Is artist choice selected for the compliant run.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Standard video wrapper folders such as VIDEO_TS or BDMV can resolve from parent path components.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
The Billboard MP3 year-folder special case applies only when all inventoried music files are .mp3, the folder name is a four-digit year from 1959 through 2005, and billboard appears somewhere in the path. The exported setlist filename for this special case uses the same four-digit year.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Non-compliant mode}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80{\loch
Use Non-compliant mode when folder names vary or contain partial/uncertain metadata. Non-compliant mode uses more evidence and tries to fill missing metadata without overwriting earlier trusted fields.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Reads FLAC ARTIST, ALBUMARTIST, ALBUM, and DATE tags before path artist fallback. Tag values containing unknown or track are treated as blank for artist purposes.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Searches folder and path text for artist, date, venue, and location clues, including known artist names and aliases.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Aggregates related wrapper/part folders such as CD1/CD2/CD3 under one logical show when appropriate.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Uses selected setlist header metadata for date, artist, venue, and location fallback before track names or hash/checksum sections.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Uses eTreeDB and setlist.fm only when enabled, and only to fill blanks or report observations.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Commas in unnumbered song lists do not need to be followed by spaces; TLO treats \u8220\'93Song A,Song B,Song C\u8221\'94 the same as \u8220\'93Song A, Song B, Song C\u8221\'94 when the item count matches the audio files.}
\par \trowd\trqc\ltrrow\trkeep\trpaddft3\trpaddt0\trpaddfl3\trpaddl0\trpaddfb3\trpaddb0\trpaddfr3\trpaddr0\clpadft3\clpadt108\clpadfr3\clpadr108\clcbpat23\cellx10368\pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\intbl\sb0\sa20{\loch
Practical choice: When in doubt, start with non-compliant mode for mixed real-world collections. Use compliant mode when you deliberately organized the folders to match the supported naming patterns and want those names trusted.}\cell\row\pard \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80\loch

\par \pard\plain \s1\rtlch\af14\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb480\sa0\keepn\cf17\f8\fs32\b\dbch\af10{\loch
10. Online lookup options}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80{\loch
Online lookup is optional. It is used to fill missing venue/location fields after artist and a full yyyy-mm-dd date are known. Later sources do not overwrite nonblank metadata found earlier; non-equivalent disagreements are reported as observations in the summary log.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
etreeDB checkbox or --etree-lookup: uses eTreeDB first among online sources. When tagging is enabled, the same option can also allow a last-resort eTreeDB song-title lookup if local setlist titles are not usable.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
setlist.fm checkbox or --setlistfm-lookup: uses setlist.fm as a last resort only when etreeDB does not return usable venue/location data. On the command line, --setlistfm-lookup requires --etree-lookup. In the GUI, selecting setlist.fm automatically selects etreeDB. If the same lookup response already contains song rows, TLO may reuse those cached rows for tagging; it does not make a separate setlist.fm call just to find track titles.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
setlist.fm requires SETLISTFM_API_KEY in the environment.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
setlist.fm requests are rate-limited to one request every 600 milliseconds across local workers and capped at 1,400 calls per inventory run.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
For U.S. lookup results, show names use Artist Date Venue City StateCode. Non-U.S. results use Artist Date Venue City Country.}
\par \pard\plain \s81\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af9\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\li360\lin360\ri144\rin144\sb40\sa80\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f9\fs17\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sb60\sa120{\loch
Command-line examples:\line tlo-gi.exe --TLOHome C:\\TLOHome --etree-lookup\line python3 tlo-gi.py --TLOHome "$TLOHome" --compliant --compliant-artist-mode as-is --etree-lookup --setlistfm-lookup}
\par \pard\plain \s1\rtlch\af14\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb480\sa0\keepn\cf17\f8\fs32\b\dbch\af10{\loch
11. Tagging functions}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
The tagging window is used when you want TLO to write tags to audio files. Its window title bar reads TLO Tagger GUI v1.0 Build 321. Inside the window, the single bold heading is Traders Little Helper\u8482\'99 Tagger App; there is no second in-window version heading. The exact layout may vary slightly by platform, but the main choices and actions are the same.}
\par
The tagger also creates CorruptFlacs.txt in TLOHome. If a FLAC file cannot be opened or written during tagging, TLO appends the complete file path to that file so bad FLACs can be reviewed separately from other tagging errors.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\loch

\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Figure 6. Tagging window example. The circles and arrows highlight the main steps: choose the folder or tag path, choose the mode, click Tag, and read the status area.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
How to use the tagging window}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Choose the folder or root you want to tag.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Choose Compliant when folder names are already organized in the stricter pattern. When prompted, choose Master if you want String1 checked against the artist database, or As-Is if you want String1 used exactly as the artist. Choose Non-compliant when names vary and you want TLO to use its more flexible matching.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Click Tag to start writing tags.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Use Quit to close the tagging window. If tagging is still running, Quit requests tagger cancellation, closes only the tagging window, and leaves the main Inventory GUI open; conflicting main-window actions may stay unavailable briefly until the tagger worker stops.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
The Tagger window is intentionally compact. Starting in Build 298, the Tagging Path field and output console are about half as wide as earlier builds, and the mode summary wraps rather than forcing a wider window.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
When tagging finishes, the Tagger window prints an elapsed-time line after the completion output. Runs under one hour display as M:SS; longer runs display as H:MM:SS.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Use Review Txt Files when you want to review the related text/setlist material during the process.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Read the status area for progress messages and results.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Standalone Tag button / tlo-tag}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80{\loch
The standalone Tag function writes audio file tags for folders under TLOHome/readyForXfer by default. A supplied tagPath overrides readyForXfer only for tagging; it is not an inventory or updater input.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
In compliant tagging, folder rules provide artist/album metadata.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
In non-compliant tagging, the tagger uses inventory-style music discovery, selected setlists, wrapper aggregation, FLAC tag sampling, and metadata extraction.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
In WSL/Linux, the Tagging Path may be entered as a Windows-style drive path such as P:\\tagtest; TLO converts it to /mnt/p/tagtest before running the tagger. On native Windows, enter the normal Windows path.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
When a selected setlist exists, it supplies track titles and normalized track numbers. Numbered tracks may start at 0 or 1, may use labels such as track 1, t01:, d1t01, or cd1t01, may use side-letter labels such as A01/B05, may use CD/set-prefixed numbers such as 101/201, and may restart at 1 for a new disc or set. A restart can be marked by a Set/Disc/CD heading or can be implicit: if an established numbered list ascends and then restarts at 1, TLO accepts the reset once the next parsed row continues to 2. Blank lines are not required. The written track numbers remain sequential across the full show.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Numbered song lists may also span large gaps in the text. For example, a setlist can list tracks 1 through 12, include explanatory notes, source URLs, personnel text, or blank lines, and then continue with track 13 as long as the numbered rows still continue or reset correctly. Patch notes and checksum/hash sections still stop song-title parsing.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
If a strong numbered setlist has fewer titles than audio files during inventory-time tagging, TLO can keep the known setlist titles and write Unknown only for the unmatched extra audio files. This is used conservatively so notes and revision text do not become song titles.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
auCDtect report lines such as "101 Song.wav: track looks like CDDA with probability 100%" are treated as technical verification output, not songs. TLO ignores those rows and does not use them as track titles.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Ordinal event/header lines such as "9th Annual Eddie Moore Jazz Festival" are also ignored as track titles. TLO continues looking for the actual numbered song list later in the file, including Early/Late show sections that restart numbering.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Tagging writes zero-padded track numbers: 01, 02, 03, and so on for folders with 99 or fewer tracks; 001, 002, 003, and so on for folders with more than 99 tracks. If eTreeDB fallback is enabled, returned eTreeDB song titles are used only when the eTreeDB title count matches the folder music-file count. When TLO writes tags, it also clears old TRACKTOTAL, DISCNUMBER, and DISCTOTAL values so stale disc/total metadata does not remain from earlier tagging.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
When Convert shn is selected, the Tagger, Tag in Place During Inventory, and Tag Copy During Inventory convert SHN files to FLAC before tagging. The converter is bundled with the native app build.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
When no setlist exists, track titles can fall back to usable song names extracted from audio filenames. If filenames do not contain usable titles, titles can fall back to eTreeDB song titles if eTreeDB lookup is enabled and Artist plus yyyy-mm-dd Date are known; if eTreeDB is not usable, the standalone Tagger can now fall back to existing audio Title tags. Generic existing titles such as d1t01, Track 1, bare numbers, unknown, or untitled are not treated as real song titles.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
When a setlist has no numbered tracks, TLO can use comma-separated fallback text if the item count matches the number of music files, or use long comma-separated lines as titles when the line count matches the file count. SET ONE/SET TWO style comma-list sections are supported, and medley arrows inside a comma item, such as Jam>Flute Down, are kept inside the title instead of being split. These fallback choices are noted in the tag success/error logs and summary.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Setlists are not assumed to be stored beside the music files. TLO may also find them in a small parent release folder or in a sibling information folder when the folder layout appears to be one compact release rather than a broad artist directory.}
\par \pard\plain \s81\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af9\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\li360\lin360\ri144\rin144\sb40\sa80\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f9\fs17\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af13\langfe1033\sb60\sa120{\loch
Windows example:\line C:\\TLOHome\\apps\\Windows\\tlo-tag.exe --TLOHome C:\\TLOHome --tag-path C:\\Incoming\\ToTag\line \line WSL/Linux example:\line "$TLOHome/apps/Linux/tlo-tag" --TLOHome "$TLOHome" --compliant\line \line eTreeDB title fallback example:\line "$TLOHome/apps/Linux/tlo-tag" --TLOHome "$TLOHome" --etree-lookup}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Tag in Place and Tag Copy During Inventory}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80{\loch
Tag in Place During Inventory writes audio tags to the inventoried music files during a full inventory run. Tag Copy During Inventory copies each music folder to a Destination of Copies, tags the copy, and keeps the original source folder in the inventory. Tag Copy/Delete Original transfers each resolved folder to the destination, tags the destination, deletes the original after verification when needed, and inventories the destination copy/move target.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
If no show name can be determined, TLO leaves the original folder untouched: it does not tag, rename, copy, move, or copy/delete that unidentified show. The path remains available for unresolved-show reporting.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
If no setlist can be used, titles can fall back to usable filename-derived titles first. If filenames do not provide usable titles, eTreeDB song titles may be used when the eTreeDB option is enabled and Artist plus yyyy-mm-dd Date are known. Existing audio Title tags remain the last-resort source for both inventory-time tagging and the standalone/GUI Tagger.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
When the GUI or command line is launched with debug enabled, inventory-time tagging writes diagnostic files to TLOHome/debug only for setlist/title problems. The debug .txt filename is based on the generated inventory setlist filename for the show. Bad audio files, invalid FLAC files, SHN conversion errors, and per-file tag-write failures are not copied to debug; they are listed in the tag error log with the full file path.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
A title literally written in the setlist as unknown, ??, (unknown title), intro, outro, banter, or similar is treated as a supplied setlist title. Generated Unknown fallback titles are logged when applicable, but neither literal nor generated Unknown titles create a debug .txt file merely because they were tagged. Debug copies remain for skipped parse/count diagnostics when a readable selected setlist exists.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Compliant mode still does not read FLAC tags for metadata decisions, but inventory-time tagging can write tags as an output action. Rename Compliantly is independent of tagging. During Full Inventory, selecting Rename Compliantly with neither Tag in Place nor Tag Copy and with no Tag Copy/Delete Original destination renames the identified original folder in place and does not write audio tags. With Tag in Place, the original is renamed before tagging. With Tag Copy or Tag Copy/Delete Original, the destination folder receives the compliant Show Name.}
\par \pard\plain \s1\rtlch\af14\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb480\sa0\keepn\cf17\f8\fs32\b\dbch\af10{\loch
12. Add Shows incremental updater}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
The Add Shows window is used when you want to bring new shows into an existing TLO collection without rerunning a full inventory. Its title bar reads TLO Inventory Updater v1.0 Build 321, and the visible banner reads Traders Little Helper\u8482\'99 Inventory Update App. It uses the Compliant and Rename Compliantly settings from the main window when it is opened.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\loch

\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Figure 7. Add Shows window example. The circles and arrows highlight the usual flow: set the volume, review the folders, check for duplicates, process the new shows, and then apply the final folder action.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
How to use the Add Shows window}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Set the current storage drive/volume so new rows are labeled the way you want.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Review the folder list and any possible matches.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Use Check for Duplicates before processing when you want TLO to look for possible existing matches.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Use Process New Shows to add the new show information.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Use Review Selected Txt Files to inspect the related text files when needed.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
When duplicates or upgrades need a decision, use the duplicate-handling choices shown in the window.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Finish with Process Folders (Delete/Move) to apply the folder action you selected.}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80{\loch
Add Shows (incremental) adds new content without rerunning the entire full inventory. It works with folders under TLOHome/readyForXfer and moves processed folders into staged or dups depending on duplicate checks.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Before opening, the updater checks for TLOHome/deleteBackupFolders.bat on Windows or TLOHome/deleteBackupFolders.sh on WSL/Linux. If it exists, a backup alert lets you continue or abort opening the updater.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Current Backup/Storage Drive and Volume defaults from TLOCurrentStorage or --current-storage-volume and is written into bootlist.csv rows for newly staged folders.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Check for Duplicates compares new folders against the existing inventory using dates and known artist aliases where available.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Compliant mode in the updater checks String1 Date String2 first, then String1 - String2. The same Master or As-Is artist choice applies. If String1 is not recognized as a known artist in Master mode, the folder can still be processed as new using the folder text. Add Shows does not have its own Compliant checkbox; change Compliant in the main window before opening Add Shows.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Process New Shows scans top-level readyForXfer folders, creates setlists, adds bootlist rows, and moves folders to staged or dups. If Rename Compliantly is checked in the main window, Add Shows renames accepted folders in place using the resolved Show Name before moving them to staged. Add Shows ignores Tag in Place and Tag Copy; it does not copy folders for tagging and does not ask for Destination of Copies. If no bootlist.csv exists yet, Add Shows warns that it can create a new bootlist from readyForXfer but is normally used after a full inventory. The Current Backup/Storage Drive and Volume field must be filled in before this first Add Shows run can continue, and the user must confirm before Add Shows processes new folders as the first inventory output.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Process Potential Duplicate/Upgrades, shown on two lines in the button, opens one duplicate-handling window per duplicate candidate.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Review Selected Txt Files opens read-only setlist review windows. If no rows are selected, it reviews all listed matches.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Process Folders (Delete/Move) applies the selected duplicate-handling choice, moves accepted new folders to staged, updates bootlist.csv, and closes the duplicate window.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Delete New / Keep Old deletes the new duplicate candidate. If no old rows are selected, the note Keep all when none selected applies.}
\par \trowd\trqc\ltrrow\trkeep\trpaddft3\trpaddt0\trpaddfl3\trpaddl0\trpaddfb3\trpaddb0\trpaddfr3\trpaddr0\clpadft3\clpadt108\clpadfr3\clpadr108\clcbpat23\cellx10368\pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\intbl\sb0\sa20{\loch
Function locking: Full Inventory, Add Shows, and Tag are separate functions. Start only one at a time from the main GUI.}\cell\row\pard \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80\loch

\par \pard\plain \s1\rtlch\af14\afs28\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb480\sa0\keepn\cf17\f8\fs32\b\dbch\af10{\loch
13. Search app}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
The TLO Search app is included in the cross-platform distribution. It searches the completed TLO inventory and related setlist text files after Full Inventory or Add Shows creates the searchable outputs.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Main search window}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\loch

\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Figure 8. Search app main window example. The circles and arrows show the usual flow: set TLOHome, enter a search, choose whether to use Deep search, adjust the font if wanted, and then run the search.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
TLOHome points the search app to the correct TLO folder.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Search accepts ordinary text and the Boolean forms described elsewhere in the manual, such as |AND|, |OR|, and parentheses.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
The search box keeps a history of earlier searches.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
When Deep is off, the app searches the main inventory results.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
When Deep is on, the app searches inside the setlist text files. Deep search requires a non-empty search term.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
The Font selector changes the display font family in the app and the results windows.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
You can press Enter in the Search box or click Execute search.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
At startup, the app can preload the first search from the --find command-line value or from the clipboard.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Results windows}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\loch

\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
Figure 9. Search results window example. The standard results window lists matching rows from the inventory. A similar window is used for Deep results, but it lists matching files.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
The standard results window shows matching Show and Volume/Path rows.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
You can select one or many rows.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Use View, press Enter, or double-click a selected row to open the related setlist text.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Use Close to close the results window.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
If many rows or files are selected, the app asks for confirmation before opening them all.}
\par \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10{\loch
Shortcut and startup behavior}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033\sl252\slmult1\sb0\sa80{\loch
The included tlo-gsi application reads the completed TLOHome outputs and lets you search the inventory.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
The search app should be launched after TLOHome has a bootlist.csv and setlist files from inventory or Add Shows.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
After extracting the distribution, use the optional Start Menu shortcut steps in Section 4 to pin TLO Search, open the shortcut folder, set Start in, and assign a hot key.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Copy the edited shortcut into the Startup folder when TLO Search should open at login.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
Use Ctrl-Shift-C as the example hot key, or choose a different unused shortcut key if Windows or another app already uses it.}
