Useful when reviewing standalone tagging or Tag During Inventory output.}\cell\row\pard \pard\plain \s2\rtlch\af14\afs26\ab \ltrch\hich\af8\loch\keep\sb200\sa0\keepn\cf18\f8\fs26\b\dbch\af10\pagebb{\loch
Relationship between logs}
\par \pard\plain \s0\rtlch\af14\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\lang1033\langfe1033\hich\af2\loch\sl276\slmult1\ql\widctlpar\sb0\sa200\ltrpar\hyphpar0\f2\fs20\cf0\lang1033\kerning0\dbch\af11\langfe1033{\loch
The Postprocess timing section in summary.log is the quickest way to identify whether a slow finish was caused by log aggregation, setlist export, bootlist writing, unidentified-show output, or summary writing.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
summary.log is the user-facing overview. Use it first.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
The numbered worker logs provide detail behind the summary. They are mainly for diagnosis and review. In Build 215 and later, the complete-path log stores only one representative full media-file path when a folder is identified as containing music/video, rather than listing directories, setlist candidates, every media file, or a separate marker record.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
compX.log, groupsX.log, and metaX.log usually explain what was accepted into the run. compX.log keeps only the representative media path for each identified media folder. If a reused or older complete-path log contains more than one media filename from the same folder, TLO compacts it after Phase 1 so only the first representative row remains. groupsX.log and metaX.log show the derived music directory, representative media type, chosen setlist source, and any later details discovered by rescanning known folders when needed.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
deadX.log and dupsX.log usually explain why something needs attention.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
tagsX.txt and tageX.txt apply when Tag in Place During Inventory or Tag Copy During Inventory is used. The standalone/GUI Tagger writes its own tag output to tagsT.txt/tageT.txt. Tag success logs record normal status/success activity. Tag error logs record warnings, skips, cancellations, and errors with reason-code prefixes such as SKIP_TITLE_COUNT and ERROR_AUDIO_FILE when applicable.}
\par \pard\plain \s67\loch\sb0\sa200\contextualspace{\listtext\pard\plain \hich\af4\loch\f4 \u61623\'3f\tab}\ilvl0\ls1 \fi-360\li360\lin360{\loch
If the standalone/GUI Tagger processes files, tagsT.txt should contain the same status/success information shown in the tagger output window or console, while tageT.txt should contain warnings, skips, errors, completion lines that report file errors, and a problem-summary block by reason code when reason-coded problems occurred.}
